The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Adam flattens Lanka
                                                     Adam flattens Lanka
  - Bracken, Johnson ensure facile victory for Australia         TRI-SERIES            Lasith Malinga, who bagged four for 47, in Perth on Friday                           
	Perth: Adam Gilchrist hit a century in his final hometown appearance in Perth to lead Australia to a 63-run victory over Sri Lanka in Fridays tri-series match.         
	Gilchrist bowed out at the Waca with 118, scoring half of Australias all-out total of 236. It was his first one-day hundred since he made a breathtaking ton against Sri Lanka in last years World Cup final in Barbados.         
	Sri Lanka replied with 173 despite a defiant 80 from their own wicketkeeper-batsman Kumar Sangakkara, handing the hosts a bonus point for their big winning margin.         
	The victory lifted Australia to the top of the table with 12 points from four games. India are second with eight points while Sri Lanka have six at the halfway stage of the competition.         
	Sri Lanka made a flying start to their reply, piling up 71 runs in 11 overs but also losing openers Sanath Jayasuriya (12) and Tillekeratne Dilshan (11) and captain Mahela Jayawardene (21).         
	Australias pace duo of Nathan Bracken (3/21) and Mitchell Johnson (3/29) shared six wickets among them.   
	(Agencies)  
	HIGHLIGHTS
    
	Sri Lanka have now lost the last six matches they have played against Australia. Sri Lanka last beat Australia in Australia on February 10, 2006 in Adelaide. They had won by 22 runs.  
	 Adam Gilchrist scored his 16th ODI century, sixth vs Sri Lanka, 9th in Australia and second in his hometown Perth. All his hundreds have come as an opener and on winning causes. He joined Saeed Anwar, Desmond Haynes and Brian Lara who have also scored 16 hundreds in won matches. Sachin Tendulkar with 29 winning hundreds heads the list followed by Sanath Jayasuriya (22), Ricky Ponting (21) and Sourav Ganguly (18).   
	 Muttiah Muralidharan claimed his 34th stumped dismissal (Michael Clarke) to join Shane Warne with maximum number of stumped dismissals.  
	 Lasith Malinga claimed his second four-wicket haul in ODIs. His figures of four for 47 are now his best against Australia, previous best being two for 49 in the World Cup final (April 28, 2007).  
	 Brad Hogg claimed his 150th wicket in ODIs to become the sixth Australian to achieve the feat.  
